    <edge source="The insulating suits used by Peter Claney and his team during their expedition to Mercury's Brightside were the best available at the time. Each suit had an inner lining made of a fiberglass modification, which served as a reliable insulation material while avoiding the clumsiness associated with asbestos. The refrigerating unit and oxygen storage were integrated into the suit, and they recharged these components from the sledges every eight hours.&#10;&#10;The outer layer of the suits was made of a monomolecular chrome reflecting surface, which gave them a glittering appearance like Christmas trees. This reflective surface helped to minimize heat absorption from the intense Mercury sunlight. Additionally, there was a half-inch dead-air space under positive pressure between the two layers, providing further insulation and serving as a barrier against heat transfer.&#10;&#10;To ensure safety, warning thermocouples were installed in the suits, activating at 770 degrees Fahrenheit to provide early detection of any failures in the suit's insulation system, thereby preventing the wearer from being exposed to hazardous temperatures." target="1. Constant Thirst: The harsh environment of Mercury caused the explorers to experience constant and unceasing thirst due to unknown physiological and psychological reasons. Despite having access to water, they had to ration it carefully to avoid health issues like nephritis.&#10;&#10;2. Heat Regulation in Suits: The insulating suits worn by the team were designed with an inner lining made of fiberglass modification for reliable insulation against extreme heat. A refrigerating unit and oxygen storage were integrated into each suit, recharged every eight hours from sledges. Warning thermocouples were installed to alert them if the suit's insulation system failed or reached hazardous temperatures of 770 degrees Fahrenheit.&#10;&#10;3. Use of Sun-shields: During their rest periods, the team parked their Bugs (rovers) in a square formation and set up light aluminum sun-shields to reduce ambient temperature by sixty to seventy degrees. This provided some relief from the intense heat of Mercury's sunlight while they slept and ate from forward sledges using tubes for nutrition intake.&#10;&#10;These challenges indicate that the explorers faced severe physical and environmental difficulties during their eight-hour drives in the hot desert, primarily due to the extreme temperatures and dry conditions on Mercury.">
