    <edge source=" he’s got Mercury. Until then, nobody’s got Mercury. I want Mercury—but I’ll need help getting it.”&#10; &#10; &#10; I’d thought of it a thousand times and never dared consider it. Nobody had, since Wyatt and Carpenter disappeared. Mercury turns on its axis in the same time that it wheels around the Sun, which means that the Brightside is always facing in. That makes the Brightside of Mercury at perihelion the hottest place in the Solar System, with one single exception: the surface of the Sun itself.&#10; &#10; &#10; It would be a hellish trek. Only a few men had ever learned just how hellish and they never came back to tell about it. It was a real hell’s Crossing, but someday, I thought, somebody would cross it.&#10; &#10; &#10; I wanted to be along.&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; The Twilight Lab, near the northern pole of Mercury, was the obvious jumping-off place. The setup there wasn’t very extensive—a rocket landing, the labs and quarters for Sanderson’s crew sunk deep into the crust, and the tower that housed the Solar ’scope that Sanderson" target="1. Sanderson chose Mercury's twilight zone near the pole to build the Twilight Lab because this area is wider (about five miles) compared to other parts of the twilight zone, providing a more manageable temperature range for human survival and equipment operation.&#10;   &#10;2. The twilight zone on Mercury experiences less extreme temperatures than the Brightside or Darkside due to its position between these two extremes. At the pole, the twilight zone has a temperature variation of only 50 to 60 degrees, which is more suitable for sustaining human life and equipment operation compared to the scorching heat of the Brightside or the frigid cold of the Darkside.&#10;   &#10;3. The twilight zone near the pole also offers good clear observation of the Sun for about seventy out of Mercury's eighty-eight-day orbit around the Sun, providing ample opportunities for solar observations and research. This location was selected specifically for the Solar 'scope observatory project due to its relatively stable and less extreme temperature conditions compared to other areas on Mercury.">
