    <edge source="&#10; &#10; &#10; “This range here,” the Major said as we crowded around the board, “is largely inactive, according to Sanderson. But these to the south and west could be active. Seismograph tracings suggest a lot of activity in that region, getting worse down toward the equator—not only volcanic, but sub-surface shifting.”&#10; &#10; &#10; Stone nodded. “Sanderson told me there was probably constant surface activity.”&#10; &#10; &#10; The Major shrugged. “Well, it’s treacherous, there’s no doubt of it. But the only way to avoid it is to travel over the Pole, which would lose us days and offer us no guarantee of less activity to the west. Now we might avoid some if we could find a pass through this range and cut sharp east—”&#10; &#10; &#10; It seemed that the more we considered the problem, the further we got from a solution. We knew there were active volcanoes on the Brightside—even on the Darkside, though surface activity there was pretty much slowed down and localized.&#10; &#10; &#10; But there were problems of atmosphere on Brightside, as well. There" target="1. The specific challenges and potential risks of traveling through the proposed regions on the map in terms of seismic activity include active volcanoes, sub-surface shifting, and constant surface activity. These conditions can make the ground unstable and treacherous, increasing the risk of accidents or getting trapped.&#10;2. In terms of atmospheric conditions, there are also significant challenges on Brightside, such as sulfurous breezes and a yellowish mist filled with sulfurous gases. The atmosphere can be suffocating and dangerous, making it difficult to navigate and survive in.&#10;3. A possible route that could potentially minimize these risks would be to find a pass through the active range and cut sharp east, as suggested by the Major. However, this would require careful planning and preparation, including ensuring that the shifting of any ledges or crossing points has stopped or significantly reduced, confirming the stability of landing areas, and being prepared for unexpected changes due to Mercury's unpredictable surface conditions.&#10;4. Additionally, maintaining visual contact with each other at all times and possibly crossing the cleft one or two vehicles at a time could help ensure everyone's safety while crossing any shifting gray ledges or other potential hazards. Overall, careful planning, preparation, and caution will be essential to minimizing risks and ensuring a safe and successful journey through the proposed regions on the map.">
