int identified as a long, narrow ledge of gray stuff, they need to ensure that the shifting of the ledge has stopped or significantly reduced before attempting to cross. Additionally, they must confirm the stability of the landing area on the other side and be prepared for unexpected changes due to Mercury's unpredictable surface conditions, which include shifting faults, active cones, sulfurous breezes, and treacherous yellow flatlands filled with dust and gases beneath the crust.">
