    <edge source="1. Sanderson chose Mercury's twilight zone near the pole to build the Twilight Lab because this area is wider (about five miles) compared to other parts of the twilight zone, providing a more manageable temperature range for human survival and equipment operation.&#10;   &#10;2. The twilight zone on Mercury experiences less extreme temperatures than the Brightside or Darkside due to its position between these two extremes. At the pole, the twilight zone has a temperature variation of only 50 to 60 degrees, which is more suitable for sustaining human life and equipment operation compared to the scorching heat of the Brightside or the frigid cold of the Darkside.&#10;   &#10;3. The twilight zone near the pole also offers good clear observation of the Sun for about seventy out of Mercury's eighty-eight-day orbit around the Sun, providing ample opportunities for solar observations and research. This location was selected specifically for the Solar 'scope observatory project due to its relatively stable and less extreme temperature conditions compared to other areas on Mercury." target="1. Constant Thirst: The harsh environment of Mercury caused the explorers to experience constant and unceasing thirst due to unknown physiological and psychological reasons. Despite having access to water, they had to ration it carefully to avoid health issues like nephritis.&#10;&#10;2. Heat Regulation in Suits: The insulating suits worn by the team were designed with an inner lining made of fiberglass modification for reliable insulation against extreme heat. A refrigerating unit and oxygen storage were integrated into each suit, recharged every eight hours from sledges. Warning thermocouples were installed to alert them if the suit's insulation system failed or reached hazardous temperatures of 770 degrees Fahrenheit.&#10;&#10;3. Use of Sun-shields: During their rest periods, the team parked their Bugs (rovers) in a square formation and set up light aluminum sun-shields to reduce ambient temperature by sixty to seventy degrees. This provided some relief from the intense heat of Mercury's sunlight while they slept and ate from forward sledges using tubes for nutrition intake.&#10;&#10;These challenges indicate that the explorers faced severe physical and environmental difficulties during their eight-hour drives in the hot desert, primarily due to the extreme temperatures and dry conditions on Mercury.">
